<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-04-15T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-04-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="473" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d473">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">896.001 Roxas/4–1548: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Embassy in the
                                        Philippines</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">us urgent</hi>
                                </seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-04-15">April 15,
                                    1948</date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>473. Following press statement being released by President: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                    <p>“I am deeply shocked at the news of the sudden death of
                                        President Manuel Roxas of the Philippines. In his passing,
                                        the Philippine people have lost a great leader and the
                                        United States of America a true friend.</p>
                                    <p>He assumed office as President when his war-ravaged country
                                        was faced with the most staggering problems. His untimely
                                        death in itself is evidence of the energy which he brought
                                        to the restoration of the Philippines and to the service of
                                        his people. The officials of this Government with whom he
                                        came in contact have been unanimous in their praise of his
                                        far-seeing vision and statesmanship. His sure leadership of
                                        the people of the Philippines and his courageous faith in
                                        his country may well serve as an inspiration to the people
                                        of all lands.”</p>
                                </quote>
                            </p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Lovett</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>